provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:31:This workspace is building a design methodology in which diverse perspectives deliberate, produce durable specifications, and preserve the reasoning behind decisions (provenance) so future readers — human or agent — can reconstruct what was decided and what was considered. The methodology is self-hosting: it evolves by running its own process on itself.
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:59:4. **Mid vocabulary distance.** The target's vocabulary must differ from the methodology's native self-description (activities, specifications, provenance, deliberations, triggers, manifests) but overlap enough to translate.
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:61:5. **Externally legible.** The target's outcome must be readable and judgeable by someone outside this workspace who has not internalised the methodology's provenance. If the first external artefact is only interpretable by readers who have read the methodology's internal specs, no external evidence has been produced.
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:111:Your response will be committed verbatim as provenance. It will be read by synthesis in conjunction with three other perspective responses. Your positions — including positions you hold reluctantly or conditionally — are recorded at their strongest. Do not soften them to anticipate synthesis. If you hold a position in tension with your role-specific stance, record the tension explicitly; the synthesis prefers honest tension to performed alignment.
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:126:Answer the five questions and write a Meta-note per §4 of the brief. Your response will be committed verbatim as provenance.
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:129:The brief is self-contained, so I’m treating this as a provenance draft rather than a code task. I’ll answer directly from the stated criteria, leaning into targets that are not software-shaped and not the most obvious “methodology test” choices.
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:181:What would make it read as disguised methodology-talk is easy to spot. If the main document foregrounds deliberation stages, provenance jargon, trigger satisfaction, or activity mapping, it will feel internal. If it contains “design principles” but not Tuesday dinner, it will fail criterion 5. If it narrates how the methodology reasoned more than what the household should do, it will look like process theatre.
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:183:The clean way to manage this is separation. The external artefact should stand alone as the thing being designed. Provenance can exist, but as a sidecar or appendix. A reader unfamiliar with the methodology should be able to ignore provenance entirely and still say, “This is a usable dinner-system draft.”
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:199:My strongest likely difference is that I rank a household-operational target above a curriculum-style target. That is salient because it intentionally makes the first external test harder to fake with good prose. The assumption I most distrust is that the user can quickly provide enough concrete constraints for a cooking or hobby brief; if that assumption fails, shortlist order should change. My main framing concern is that Validate has only the user as an immediate reader, which can drift toward informed self-approval unless the external artefact is written to stand alone and provenance is kept separate. The outside-view strength here is lower contamination by workspace-native priors; the weakness is that I may be underestimating hidden constraints created by Sessions 001–007.
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:252:What would make it read as disguised methodology-talk is easy to spot. If the main document foregrounds deliberation stages, provenance jargon, trigger satisfaction, or activity mapping, it will feel internal. If it contains “design principles” but not Tuesday dinner, it will fail criterion 5. If it narrates how the methodology reasoned more than what the household should do, it will look like process theatre.
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:254:The clean way to manage this is separation. The external artefact should stand alone as the thing being designed. Provenance can exist, but as a sidecar or appendix. A reader unfamiliar with the methodology should be able to ignore provenance entirely and still say, “This is a usable dinner-system draft.”
provenance/008-first-external-application/01d-perspective-outsider.md:270:My strongest likely difference is that I rank a household-operational target above a curriculum-style target. That is salient because it intentionally makes the first external test harder to fake with good prose. The assumption I most distrust is that the user can quickly provide enough concrete constraints for a cooking or hobby brief; if that assumption fails, shortlist order should change. My main framing concern is that Validate has only the user as an immediate reader, which can drift toward informed self-approval unless the external artefact is written to stand alone and provenance is kept separate. The outside-view strength here is lower contamination by workspace-native priors; the weakness is that I may be underestimating hidden constraints created by Sessions 001–007.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:17:This specification defines the **access discipline** governing what the methodology reads in full at every session open versus what it preserves verbatim and accesses by explicit reference. It repairs a divergence observed at Session 022 between the methodology's normative read obligation (`methodology-kernel.md` §1 Read: "every file, every specification, every provenance record") and the operational read mechanism (paginated `Read --offset`, targeted `Grep`, harness-layer routing around oversized files).
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:19:The access discipline is a dimension separate from — and cutting across — the existing file-class ontology in `workspace-structure.md` (engine-definition / development-provenance / application-scope). A file may be engine-definition AND default-read (an active specification); development-provenance AND archive surface (a historical raw perspective).
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:39:7. Every `provenance/NNN-title/03-close.md` across all closed sessions.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:40:8. Every file in the currently-active session's provenance directory (`provenance/NNN-title/` where NNN is the current session). While the session is open, current-session provenance is default-read; on close, it becomes archive surface by exclusion (§3) unless it is a `03-close.md` (which stays default-read by §7 above).
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:55:**Outsider minority position** (§5.3 of `provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/01-deliberation.md`): 8,000-word per-file budget is the conservative-preferable value; 15,000 may be permissive. Activation warrant: if any default-read file exceeds 10,000 words (soft warning) within 5 sessions of adoption without subsequent restructure, the 8,000-word ceiling becomes the preferred revision direction.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:61:- Raw perspective files (`provenance/NNN-title/01X-perspective-<role>.md`) from closed sessions.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:63:- Deliberation synthesis files (`provenance/NNN-title/01-deliberation.md`) from closed sessions.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:64:- Decision files (`provenance/NNN-title/02-decisions.md`) from closed sessions.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:65:- Assessment files (`provenance/NNN-title/00-assessment.md`) from closed sessions.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:66:- Manifests (`provenance/NNN-title/manifests/`) from closed sessions.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:67:- Participant indexes (`provenance/NNN-title/participants.yaml`) from closed sessions.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:76:When an archive-surface record exceeds the default-read per-file budget (§2 hard ceiling), or when the archive record is produced within a current session that will otherwise push the current-session provenance directory over budget at close, the record must be structured as an **archive-pack**: a directory with a manifest plus numbered chunks, preserving byte-identical content via line-range splits only.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:81:provenance/NNN-title/archive/<slug>/
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:131:[archive: provenance/NNN-title/archive/<slug>/]
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:137:[archive: provenance/NNN-title/archive/<slug>/#chunk-02]
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:148:Per D-017 immutability (`workspace-structure.md` §provenance), once the migrating session closes, archive-pack files are immutable. Any revision to an archive-pack's content requires a new migrating session with its own decision record; the revision creates a new archive-pack and a supersession reference, not an edit of the prior pack.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:150:Archive-packs created by retroactive migration (migrating a closed session's file into archive form) use the **copy-plus-reference** discipline per Session 009 D-054 precedent: the original file at its original path is **not modified**; the archive-pack is created alongside, typically in the migrating session's own provenance directory (`provenance/<migrating-NNN>/archive/<slug>/`). The original remains at its original path as the byte-identical witness; the archive-pack provides structured access.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:152:Archive-packs created for the current session's own raws (per §9 close-time obligation) move the original content into the archive-pack structure directly (the original path becomes the archive-pack path; no duplication). Because the session is still open at the time of packing, moving is not an edit of a closed-session file.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:164:At every session close, the orchestrator measures each raw perspective file and each provenance file in the current session directory. Any file exceeding the default-read per-file hard ceiling (§2: 15,000 words) is archive-packed before session close.
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:168:1. Create `provenance/NNN-title/archive/<slug>/` where `<slug>` is a short descriptive identifier (typically matching the perspective role and question theme).
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:171:4. **Remove the original file** from the provenance root. The original content now lives in the archive-pack chunks (byte-identical); there is no duplication. (This removal is permissible during session close because D-017 immutability binds only on closed sessions.)
specifications/read-contract-v1.md:189:4. For every archive-pack in `provenance/*/archive/*/`: confirm `manifest.yaml` is well-formed with all §5 required fields; confirm `source_hash_sha256` matches the actual hash of concatenated chunks in canonical order. `tools/validate.sh` check 21 automates this.
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:32:Absorb the full current state of the workspace. Every file, every specification, every provenance record. If the workspace is under version control, understand the recent history. Build a complete picture before changing anything.
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:69:This activity produces the richest provenance. The record should capture not just conclusions but the reasoning that led to them.
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:103:Commit provenance to the workspace. Ensure all deliberations, decisions, and the reasoning behind them are captured in the session's provenance directory.
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:113:- A statement of what the next session should address is included in the session log or provenance
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:117:- **Read prior provenance before proposing.** If an idea was considered and rejected in a prior session, do not silently re-propose it. Cite the prior rejection and explain what has changed.
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:119:- **Preserve all provenance.** Do not delete historical records, even when they feel outdated.
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:127:- Changes to the kernel are recorded in provenance like any other decision
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:134:1. Review the most recent session's provenance and check that all nine activities were performed (or that their omission was explained — e.g., Convene is not needed for pure validation work)
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:138:5. Check that no provenance from closed sessions has been modified
specifications/methodology-kernel-v1.md:139:6. Ask: did the session's Read activity successfully use prior provenance to understand past decisions? If not, the provenance format or depth may need revision
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-deliberation.md:105:**Convergence on no-backfill.** All four perspectives unambiguously reject full backfill of D-001–D-036. The immutability rule (D-017, workspace-structure §provenance) is honored. Even the Implementer, who would accept presence-gating that coincidentally produces the same effect, does not advocate backfill [`01b`, Q3].
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-deliberation.md:107:**Coverage: separate retrospective artefact.** Skeptic uniquely proposes: "If future work demands unified classification of all 36 prior decisions, that is a separate session's job, conducted as a documented reclassification exercise with its own provenance, producing a new artefact (e.g., `provenance/session-NNN/reclassification.md`) that references the prior decisions without editing them" [`01c`, Q3]. Outsider echoes more briefly: "If a future session wants old-trigger coverage for historical study, it should produce a separate migration index or retrospective analysis artifact, not edit the preserved records" [`01d`, Q3].
specifications/methodology-kernel-v3.md:33:Absorb what the session will reason from before changing anything. In every session this includes **workspace reading**: the full current state of the workspace — every file, every specification, every provenance record, and, where relevant, recent version-control history. Build a complete picture of the workspace's own state.
