provenance/010-household-decision-protocol/02-decisions.md:170:**OI-014 (Domain-actor receipt shape variance):** **Monitor, with a light variant note.** Session 010's expected domain-validation receipt shape is **two-person (user and wife), single written report via the user, timely**. This is a *minor variant* of Session 008's single-user-self-report pattern — it introduces a second participant but not a categorically different receipt shape. OI-014's activation trigger ("materially differs") has *not* fired; the two-person-via-one-report pattern is close enough to Session 008's to be treated as within-variance. A more substantially different receipt shape (independent expert evaluation; observational study; non-timely feedback; multi-party with independent reports) would activate OI-014. Monitor.
provenance/010-household-decision-protocol/02-decisions.md:172:**No new open issues opened in Session 010.** The three new watchpoints (WX-10-1 through WX-10-5 per D-058) are recorded in Session 010's provenance, not in `open-issues.md`, because they are artefact-design learnings for future external-artefact work rather than methodology-level open questions.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:38:  differs. Frontmatter is file-level metadata for provenance tracking,
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:50:This workspace is building a design methodology in which diverse perspectives deliberate, produce durable specifications, and preserve reasoning (provenance) so future readers — human or agent — can reconstruct what was decided and what was considered. The methodology is self-hosting: it evolves by running its own process on itself. The methodology advances by **sessions**. Each session performs a set of nine activities (Read, Assess, Convene, Deliberate, Decide, Produce, Validate, Record, Close). Each session produces one increment.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:74:- **Distinct vocabulary** that has emerged rather than been imposed: the nine activities; provenance; perspectives; kernel; watchpoints; stance briefs; manifests; the G/O/K/S criterion-package; triggers_met.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:75:- **Characteristic patterns.** Preservation of superseded specifications by version (v1, v2, v3) with explicit `supersedes`/`superseded-by` pointers. Per-decision trigger annotations making multi-agent and non-Claude participation machine-checkable. A recurring structure where external artefacts ship into `applications/NNN-slug/` alongside their provenance directory.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:112:**Q5. Refuse to name — Skeptic-oriented, Session 001 dissent carried forward.** Session 001's Skeptic and Minimalist positions (names ossify; name creates attachment; naming is premature) are preserved in the workspace's provenance. Those positions have had eleven sessions to be falsified. Are they falsified? Argue the refuse-to-name case at its strongest. Identity accumulation is a fact; naming is a commitment; the two are not the same. What evidence would be required before naming is clearly the right move rather than a defensible move? If Session 012 should decline to name, what's the form of that decline — does OI-001 remain open with updated notes; is the question retired; does it become "named only if the methodology is adopted externally"? Even perspectives who favour naming should engage this question seriously and explain why they reject the refuse-to-name case.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:114:**Q6. What naming changes.** Does naming the methodology change what the methodology *is*, or only how it's referenced? A name pulls future self-presentation into its shape — a methodology called "Something Kernel" accentuates the kernel; a methodology called "Something Provenance" accentuates provenance; a methodology called by a neutral-sounding name accentuates whichever parts later sessions choose to foreground. Name at least one concrete way your preferred name (from Q2 and Q3) would steer future self-presentation or reasoning. Name at least one way it would not — a property of the methodology the name *won't* privilege that remains available to future sessions. If you're refusing to name (per Q5), describe what staying unnamed steers the methodology toward or away from.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:130:Your response will be committed verbatim as provenance. It will be read by synthesis in conjunction with three other perspective responses. Your positions — including positions you hold reluctantly or conditionally — are recorded at their strongest. Do not soften them to anticipate synthesis. If you hold a position in tension with your role-specific stance, record the tension explicitly; the synthesis prefers honest tension to performed alignment.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:136:You are a non-Claude participant (external LLM). Your task is to provide an independently-trained perspective on this naming question. You do not share Claude's training provenance; where your positions diverge from what Claude-family perspectives would produce, that divergence is the value you add.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:171:The strongest evidence is not that the methodology is complete. It is that it now has a recognisable recurring form that an outside reader could distinguish from generic process language. Three markers matter most to me. First, the nine-activity kernel is no longer a loose aspiration; it has persisted long enough to function as a stable frame, and Sessions 009 and 011 show the frame being refined symmetrically rather than replaced. That is identity, not just motion. Second, the preservation discipline is unusually specific: versioned specs, explicit `supersedes` / `superseded-by` pointers, decision records with rejected alternatives, and provenance treated as first-class reconstruction material. That is a strong differentiator. Third, the methodology has crossed from pure self-description into external artefact production: two applications, one positively validated out-of-session, plus repeated multi-perspective deliberation with non-Claude participation. That means the method is not only describing itself; it is being exercised.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:189:3. `Trace`. [external analogue: design tracing and audit trace.] This foregrounds reconstructability: later readers can see how a decision came to be. It fits the methodology’s provenance ethic and its refusal to erase superseded reasoning. What it hides is synthesis and production; `Trace` risks sounding like an audit tool rather than a generative method. Collision check: high. `Trace` is an extremely common software and product term.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:193:5. `Loom`. [external analogue: a device that turns threads into fabric.] This emphasises the methodology as apparatus rather than doctrine. It is simple to say and memorable. It also fits the fact that the method produces external artefacts rather than only internal discussion. What it understates is provenance; a loom says more about production than about preserved reasoning. Collision check: high. I know multiple software, network, and crypto-adjacent uses.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:208:The main tradeoff is between fit and legibility. Names with high internal fit often become overdescriptive or jargon-heavy. Names with high legibility are often common words with severe collision problems. There is also a tradeoff between resonance and ossification: naming after the current “kernel” or “provenance” emphasis would feel precise now but age badly if later sessions redistribute emphasis.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:213:2. `Braid`. Better speakability than `Selvedge`, and still faithful to the multi-perspective structure. It falls because collision risk is materially worse and because it underplays provenance.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:215:4. `Trace`. Strong fit to provenance, but too collision-heavy and too close to a description of one function rather than the whole method.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:242:On trigger implications, this is the smallest blast radius. It likely requires ordinary spec-addition coverage and provenance recording, but it should avoid D-023-triggering revisions to the kernel, multi-agent deliberation spec, or validation approach, because the name is being recorded as identity metadata rather than as a structural kernel change. By contrast, renaming the kernel itself would require a kernel revision, supersession handling, and the heavier trigger story that comes with kernel edits. Putting the name first in `PROMPT.md` would make the operational prompt the primary identity carrier; that is too sticky and too constitutive for a decision that should remain mainly referential.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:264:If the chosen name is `Selvedge`, future self-presentation will tilt toward a particular account of what is distinctive here: not merely that the methodology has stages, but that it preserves the edges that keep reasoning from unraveling. That will likely make future writers foreground version preservation, explicit provenance, and the combination of multiple strands without erasure. It may also encourage a more disciplined claim about external artefacts: not “we have a grand theory,” but “we have a way of making durable, inspectable increments.” I think that is a good steering effect, because it emphasises the methodology’s strongest actual differentiator.
provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md:287:The strongest evidence is not that the methodology is complete. It is that it now has a recognisable recurring form that an outside reader could distinguish from generic process language. Three markers matter most to me. First, the nine-activity kernel is no longer a loose aspiration; it has persisted long enough to function as a stable frame, and Sessions 009 and 011 show the frame being refined symmetrically rather than replaced. That is identity, not just motion. Second, the preservation discipline is unusually specific: versioned specs, explicit `supersedes` / `superseded-by` pointers, decision records with rejected alternatives, and provenance treated as first-class reconstruction material. That is a strong differentiator. Third, the methodology has crossed from pure self-description into external artefact production: two applications, one positively validated out-of-session, plus repeated multi-perspective deliberation with non-Claude participation. That means the method is not only describing itself; it is being exercised.
