provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:22:This workspace is building a domain-general design methodology in which diverse perspectives deliberate, produce durable specifications, and preserve the reasoning behind decisions (provenance) so that future readers — human or agent — can reconstruct not just what was decided but what was considered and why. The methodology is self-hosting: it evolves by applying its own process to itself.
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:67:**Q2. Placement.** Where does the field live in a session's provenance?
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:71:- Option C: a new per-session manifest file (e.g., `decisions.manifest.yaml`) under the provenance directory.
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:84:Specify: which retroactivity policy is right, what marks the boundary (date, session number, artefact-presence heuristic), what `validate.sh` does when it encounters a pre-adoption decision record, and whether backfilling counts as editing immutable provenance (Session 004 D-017 and workspace-structure §provenance/ mandate immutability; a retroactive addition arguably violates that mandate — or arguably is a schema migration that accompanies the rule's introduction).
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:141:| 10 | No uncommitted changes to provenance files (heuristic) | Warning | unconditional |
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:156:Decision records live in `02-decisions.md` within each session's provenance directory. Each decision is a Markdown section of this form:
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:225:You are The Archivist. Your concern is what a reader *decades later* — human or agent — can reconstruct from the provenance. You care about:
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:229:- **Unambiguity.** A `triggers_met:` entry must mean one thing. The field's absence must also mean one thing (unevaluated? not applicable? written before the field existed?). Conflating these is a provenance failure.
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:230:- **Immutability.** Prior provenance records are immutable under the workspace rules. A retroactive backfill writes new content into closed sessions' files. Whether that is a violation of immutability or a schema migration accompanying a rule's introduction is a judgement call the session must make. You hold the stricter position unless convinced otherwise.
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:233:Your bias: **fewer, stronger, well-documented fields beat more, weaker, unclear ones.** When you choose to defer backfilling, record why in terms an archivist reading decades later can follow. When you choose to backfill, record the one-time migration as a visible event in provenance — not as a silent edit.
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:257:- You are sceptical of retroactive backfilling. Prior provenance is supposed to be immutable. If Session 006 rewrites Sessions 001–005's decision files to add a new field, that edits closed sessions' provenance; even if the edit is "additive" in spirit, it breaks the strict immutability the workspace has treated as axiomatic. Argue whether the immutability rule accommodates schema-migrations-on-adoption or whether it does not.
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:288:The Outsider perspective returns its response as stdout from `codex exec`; the convener commits that output **verbatim including the Codex banner** (model id, session id, tokens) as `01d-perspective-outsider.md`. The banner is signal — it is the non-Claude transport's provenance record, and editing it would defeat the faithfulness guarantee.
provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/01-brief-shared.md:290:**Halt rule.** If any Claude perspective fails (error, refusal, malformed response), the deliberation proceeds if at least three valid responses exist. If the Outsider fails (CLI error, refusal, empty response), the session writes `provenance/006-triggers-met-schema/STATUS.md` naming the failure and halts synthesis until the Outsider's response is committed or the session formally opts out. This is the D-021 Shape A halt enforcement.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:32:This workspace is building a design methodology in which diverse perspectives deliberate, produce durable specifications, and preserve reasoning (provenance) so future readers — human or agent — can reconstruct what was decided and what was considered. The methodology is self-hosting: it evolves by running its own process on itself. The methodology advances by **sessions**. Each session performs a set of nine activities (Read, Assess, Convene, Deliberate, Decide, Produce, Validate, Record, Close). Each session produces one increment.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:38:The methodology-kernel's §1 Read activity, as currently written, describes absorbing the workspace's state: every file, every specification, every provenance record. This works for the self-hosting case, where the thing a session is reasoning about is the methodology's own artefacts.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:42:1. The **workspace state** in the sense the kernel currently names — existing specifications, prior provenance, open issues, tools, SESSION-LOG. The methodology's self-knowledge.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:55:> Absorb the full current state of the workspace. Every file, every specification, every provenance record. If the workspace is under version control, understand the recent history. Build a complete picture before changing anything.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:112:**Q3. Scope of "domain reading."** What exactly is domain reading? Possibilities include: (a) user-stated constraints passed in the session's opening messages; (b) pretrained knowledge the orchestrating agent brings; (c) pretrained knowledge the deliberation perspectives bring (which is delivered via the brief, not read from anywhere); (d) explicit research during the session (web searches, document lookup); (e) external reference materials the user or operator cites; (f) all of the above. Where are the boundaries? For each inclusion you propose, name how the methodology keeps provenance of what was read — PROMPT.md's "do not silently import" rule forbids unflagged external inputs. If you propose that perspective pretraining counts as domain reading, explain how that reconciles with `multi-agent-deliberation.md` v3's "perspectives reason from the brief" constraint.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:130:Your response will be committed verbatim as provenance. It will be read by synthesis in conjunction with three other perspective responses. Your positions — including positions you hold reluctantly or conditionally — are recorded at their strongest. Do not soften them to anticipate synthesis. If you hold a position in tension with your role-specific stance, record the tension explicitly; the synthesis prefers honest tension to performed alignment.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:165:> Absorb the current basis of the session before changing anything. In every session this includes **workspace reading**: the current state of the workspace, its specifications, provenance records, open issues, available tools, and, where relevant, recent version-control history. When the session produces or revises an artifact for use outside the workspace, it also includes **domain reading**: the explicit domain inputs the work depends on, including user-stated constraints, cited external materials, and any research deliberately introduced into the session.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:173:On naming, I do favour “workspace reading” and “domain reading.” I do not love the second term; naming is a power move, and “domain reading” could easily become a bucket for anything convenient. But the kernel section is about Read as an activity, so the names should describe modes of reading, not only classes of material. I considered “workspace reading” plus “domain inputs.” That is more precise about provenance, but asymmetrical: one side names an activity, the other names a source type. I also considered leaving the senses unnamed and just enlarging the prose. I reject that because unnamed distinctions are precisely the kind that later sessions re-argue.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:181:I still prefer not to follow the precedent structurally. My preferred structure is short in-paragraph elaboration, with a second paragraph for the provenance constraint, as in the text I proposed in Q1. The reason is not aesthetic; it is conceptual. In §7, the two senses are genuinely different validation operations. Workspace validation and domain validation ask different questions of different actors and may complete on different timelines. Sub-sections make sense there because the activity itself branches. Read is not like that. Read remains one receptive act with two objects of attention. Giving it formal sub-sections would imply a stronger bifurcation than the methodology has actually established.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:193:User-stated constraints in the opening messages are clearly in scope. They define the problem, the target actor, and often the safety or suitability envelope. Their provenance is straightforward: the session transcript already contains them, and the brief or provenance record can cite them as the session’s stated domain constraints. External materials explicitly cited by the user or operator are also in scope. Their provenance should be recorded at source level: what the material was, who introduced it, and why it mattered. Explicit research during the session is also in scope, provided it is deliberate and recorded. Provenance there should include the research question, the source consulted, and the result used. I would not let “I looked around” count as domain reading without that minimal trail.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:197:The nearest concession I would make is this: if the session brief itself explicitly contains a summary of external domain material, then that summary is part of the session’s domain inputs. But even there, provenance should say what kind of thing it is. A brief-authored synthesis of outside knowledge is not the same as a primary source, and not the same as the model’s tacit prior. “All of the above” is therefore the wrong answer. It is exactly the kind of category inflation that makes provenance look tidy while becoming less truthful.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:207:That text could live as the second paragraph of §1, or the final sentence could be a short pointer to the deliberation spec. I slightly prefer putting the first three sentences in §1 and the stance-brief sentence as either a short final clause or a pointer, because the stance-brief rule is procedural detail about one deliberation format, while the provenance rule is kernel-level.
provenance/011-w1-kernel-read-revision/01d-perspective-outsider.md:223:I expect at least some other perspectives to accept formal §1 sub-sections mirroring §7 and to treat model pretraining as part of “domain reading” once it is surfaced in the brief. I diverge on both points. I think sub-sections would over-harden a still-unstable category, and I think calling pretraining “reading” is epistemically sloppy in a methodology that claims provenance. The assumption I most distrust in the brief is that external-domain work is naturally an extension of self-hosting work rather than a peer case the kernel should name more neutrally. My main framing concern is the ratchet: the brief asks for a revision, but the more important question is whether the kernel is the right layer for the repair.
