provenance/014-oi016-resolution/01c-perspective-skeptic.md:19:1. **Verifiable provenance of the reference solution.** The reference must have a traceable origin — a named author, a publication date, a venue or archive — such that someone reviewing the exercise later can confirm the reference was fixed *before* the methodology ran. A reference without provenance is indistinguishable from one written after the fact to match whatever the methodology produced. Concrete threshold: reference must have been published or archived at least 12 months before Session 015, with an accessible URL or citation, and a snapshot of that URL committed into the session's provenance folder as an anti-drift witness.
provenance/014-oi016-resolution/01c-perspective-skeptic.md:41:**Pre-run phase (before Session 015 opens).** A separate agent, not participating in Session 015's Produce step, performs *reference selection and constraint extraction*. This agent reads the reference, identifies the full constraint set, separates those constraints into *initial* (knowable at project start) and *emergent* (discoverable through engagement), and stores the reference itself in a provenance folder that Produce-step agents are instructed not to read. The extracted constraint set is the only thing that enters Session 015's Read step. The extractor agent's work product is committed to the repo with a hash that can be audited later.
provenance/014-oi016-resolution/01c-perspective-skeptic.md:45:**Staged constraint release.** Emergent constraints are released to the Produce step at pre-specified trigger points — e.g., "after the first Deliberate round produces a draft artefact, the orchestrator releases emergent constraint E1"; "if the draft is reviewed and passes workspace-validation, release E2." The trigger schedule is fixed before Session 015 runs; the schedule itself is part of the committed provenance. This prevents the orchestrator from adaptively staging constraints to make the methodology's output look good or bad.
provenance/014-oi016-resolution/01c-perspective-skeptic.md:116:> **Reference validation** is a *provisional substitute* for domain validation, usable only when no domain-actor is available and the alternative is producing an artefact without any external check. Select a use case with a documented proven solution whose provenance predates the session by at least 12 months; extract the constraint set from the reference; run the methodology's Produce step on the constraint set, isolated from the reference; compare the methodology's artefact to the reference using the procedure specified in [mechanism spec]; record the comparison result, explicitly including any contamination signal detected. Reference validation does **not** establish that the artefact functioned in its intended use; it establishes only whether the methodology, on a known-solved problem, produced an artefact structurally comparable to the known solution. A session that relies on reference validation must state so, must not claim domain validation, and must preserve a dissent record if any participant holds that reference validation is inadequate for the specific artefact in question.
