provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:48:The user describes the follow-up burden as continuous with the close: *"to close it, we also need to name the person responsible for following up."* The "also" is the telling word. The couple, in my reading of the user's feedback, will experience closing the decision and naming the owner as a single completed action — the moment the decision is real. Separating them into Move 5 and Move 6 would imply that a decision can be properly closed without naming who does the work, which is precisely the gap the user is flagging. A new Move 6 would also add a numbered step for what is really one beat with two parts, and Move 5's current structure (someone says it out loud; the other confirms) accommodates the second part without losing rhythm.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:92:**A mention in opening framing or after-note.** Rejected. The user's feedback is concrete — a specific sub-sequence with specific options (reuse/donate/dispose). A vague mention like "you may need to handle domain-specific wrap-up" in the opening framing fails to help the couple in front of the replaced sofa; it tells them to think about it, which they already know. The specificity of the user's feedback deserves specific artefact text.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:94:**Not at all.** Rejected, but worth naming. A strict reading of the brief's scope-discipline pressure could argue that the user's own framing — *"a few intricacies which vary by domain"* — positions disposal as the couple's judgment, not the artefact's job. I understand the argument. I reject it because the user's feedback explicitly names the sub-steps (assess / reuse / donate / dispose), which is the concreteness of someone saying "the artefact should mention this," not "the artefact should leave this to me." The conditional-note form respects the domain-specific framing while still putting the sub-sequence on the page.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:104:**No change to the opening framing or the after-note.** The opening framing mentions that the conversation doesn't have to happen all at once and that a couple can step away after Move 3; this remains accurate. The after-note isn't named in the user's feedback as needing change; I don't invent a reason.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:106:One decision I am overturning from Session 010: the Move 1 imperative-declarative frame. Session 010 chose *"Say what you're deciding — one sentence is enough"* as the opening. The user's feedback names this as too robotic. The overturn is warranted because the correction is the user's, delivered directly, and concerns the exact move under revision. This is the clearest possible case for overturning a prior design decision: the user, who is the decision's subject, says the frame doesn't work.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:112:If I were wrong and the content genuinely could not fit within existing moves, the correct response would be to expand to six moves — but the user's feedback does not force that expansion. The owner lives inside the close; the replaced-items lives inside the follow-through, which is part of the close. The existing Move 5 is the right container; it just needs a restructure and a retitle.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:116:**Should not: rewrite or re-order Moves 2, 3, or 4.** Pressure that might produce it: the Householder or Outsider perspective, reading the user's feedback about constraints surfacing during the conversation, might propose that Move 2 ("what each of you cares about") be strengthened, renamed, or re-sequenced to pick up the constraint-surfacing function I relocated to it in Q1. Why resisting matters: the user explicitly confirmed Move 2 as working. My Q1 revision says constraints "usually show up later, once you've both said what you care about and looked at what's actually available" — that's a passing reference, not a handoff that requires Move 2 to change. The reader flows into Move 2 and finds it doing its existing job; no rewrite needed. Any rewrite of Move 2 in response to my Move 1 change would be a ripple I should have contained in Move 1.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:118:**Should not: add decision-roles vocabulary (decider / driver / owner / champion / lead).** Pressure that might produce it: the C3 correction names "the person responsible for following up," which in project-management register would be called an owner or accountable party. A perspective thinking structurally might propose formalising the role with a named term — "the follower-upper," "the driver," or something similar. Why resisting matters: the artefact's register is household-casual. Introducing a decision-role noun creates the exact corporate-ification the user's feedback explicitly rejects. The correction can be made using verbs ("one of you takes it on," "whoever's following up") without naming a role. My Q2 text uses verbs deliberately.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:124:**Should not: introduce methodology-vocabulary into the artefact body.** Pressure that might produce it: this session is a methodology session and is acutely aware of its own frames (kernel, deliberation, provenance, validation). A perspective reasoning about the artefact's self-awareness might propose making the revision visibly "methodologised" — e.g., naming its own provenance trail, or using workspace-vocabulary to explain the owner role. Why resisting matters: the artefact is for the couple, not for the methodology. The brief's Section 5 names this constraint explicitly. Any methodology-vocabulary in the artefact body would be a leak from the producing context into the produced context.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:128:Two honest reactions, one on the feedback's framing, one on the deliberation's.
provenance/013-artefact-revision/01a-perspective-reviser.md:136:On the user-unavailability-for-future-domain-validation probe. I have a view, stated as the Reviser's view (language-level, not strategy-level). The methodology's next external-artefact session will need to generate an artefact for someone who cannot validate it. This has a specific language consequence: the artefact's register will have to be produced without the corrective feedback loop that caught C2 here. The methodology's internal tools for producing register — whatever they become — will need to do more of the work that was previously done by the user's post-hoc "this sentence is corporate" reaction. My concern is that the methodology may compensate for the lost feedback loop by generating more artefact — more explanation, more framing, more safety-railing — when what it should do is generate less and more precise. The opening OI for this constraint, if I had to draft its first line, would be something like: *"Without domain-actor validation available, the methodology needs internal mechanisms for register and fitness that are at least as precise as a single corrective reaction from the domain-actor."* But the word "mechanisms" is already corporate-register leaking, which is the Reviser's tell that this is past my lane. I'll leave the OI framing to the session's close activity; my contribution here is the language-level observation that lost validation pressures the methodology toward artefact-sprawl, and the artefact-sprawl pressure is the exact pressure Session 013 is already practising resisting.
