provenance/024-session-assessment/archive/024-outsider/08-chunk.md:177:I do not accept the brief’s implicit claim that the current validator-measured MAD size is 6,403 words. The live workspace now reports `specifications/multi-agent-deliberation.md` at 6,386 words, with aggregate default-read surface at 89,327 words across 35 files; 6,403 is a stale carry-forward witness from Session 023 prose, not the current live measurement. I am reasoning from the live number. See [00-assessment.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/provenance/024-session-assessment/00-assessment.md:39>) lines 39-49, [read-contract.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/specifications/read-contract.md:55>) line 55, and [engine-manifest.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/specifications/engine-manifest.md:113>) line 113.
provenance/024-session-assessment/archive/024-outsider/08-chunk.md:193:**Reasoning:** `engine-manifest.md` §5 is mechanical here: engine version increments when a file in §3 is substantively revised, a new engine-definition file is added, or one is removed/superseded; it does not increment for development-provenance changes ([engine-manifest.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/specifications/engine-manifest.md:69>) lines 69-83). A carried warning recorded in Session 024 provenance changes no engine-definition file. So under the current rule set, there is no engine-v5. That also means the Session 022 cadence minority does not escalate this session; escalation is tied to “any further engine-v-bump in Sessions 024/025/026,” not to merely discussing one ([provenance/023-session-assessment/02-decisions.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/provenance/023-session-assessment/02-decisions.md:40>) line 40, [open-issues/OI-018.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/open-issues/OI-018.md:38>) lines 38-47).
provenance/024-session-assessment/archive/024-outsider/08-chunk.md:201:**Reasoning:** The evidence is in the framing of the work itself. Session 023 explicitly set up Session 024 as “respond to the immediate 6K-soft-fire on `multi-agent-deliberation.md`” ([provenance/023-session-assessment/02-decisions.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/provenance/023-session-assessment/02-decisions.md:58>) lines 58-60). The trigger is the soft-warning threshold, not a discovered semantic incoherence in MAD’s current structure. Session 023 also preserved the Pacer minority in terms of “restructure-for-budget events” and the Skeptic minority in terms of “no restructure-for-budget event occurs” by Session 027 ([read-contract.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/specifications/read-contract.md:59>) lines 59-65). On the merits, I do not think ending the Skeptic runway is justified yet. MAD remains below the Skeptic’s 7,500-word vindication line; the new OI-004 content is still fresh and in active use; and the recalibrated budget regime still has stale literal witnesses elsewhere in spec text. That is not the fact pattern for “the structure is clearly wrong and now complete enough to split.”
provenance/024-session-assessment/archive/024-outsider/08-chunk.md:209:**Reasoning:** WX-22-1 is the risk that archive/reference machinery ceases to be repair and becomes routine non-reading. Carrying the warning keeps default-read meaning simple: there is still one governing MAD file read in full at session open. No archive indirection is introduced, and no “secondary” spec is created that may be treated socially as optional even if formally default-read. This matters because the workspace already has one documented asymmetry between the spec and actual Outsider practice: MAD says perspectives reason from the brief and “do not read workspace files,” but Session 023 close records the Outsider’s stable pattern of pre-response workspace exploration and flags the mismatch as worth future attention ([multi-agent-deliberation.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/specifications/multi-agent-deliberation.md:129>) lines 129-131, [provenance/023-session-assessment/03-close.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/provenance/023-session-assessment/03-close.md:110>) lines 110-112). I do not want a budget-response split to freeze boundaries around a file that may soon need a different substantive repair.
provenance/024-session-assessment/archive/024-outsider/08-chunk.md:211:If a future A.2 split is taken, the discipline test must be concrete: Session 025’s open assessment should list both files explicitly in its default-read surface, the same way Session 024’s assessment lists every active spec now ([00-assessment.md](</Users/ericmccowan/Development/complex-systems-engine/provenance/024-session-assessment/00-assessment.md:12>) lines 12-19). If only the “core” file gets named and the OI-004 file becomes de facto consult-only, that is laundering. For A.3, the answer is harder: archive relocation of the OI-004 or heterogeneous-participant sections would make archive access routine, because validators and human auditors would need those sections repeatedly. That would be exactly the bad pattern WX-22-1 warns about.
provenance/005-schema-enforcement/01-deliberation.md:138:`[synth]` The Archivist and Outsider align on *not failing Session 004 retroactively*; the Implementer and Skeptic align on *evaluating it with the check's honest severity (Fail for Implementer, Warning for Skeptic)*. The distinction is whether Session 004's partial schema adoption should be a source of signal or protected as provenance. `[synth]` The protectability argument is stronger: Session 004 was explicitly the bootstrap-exemption session, and a Tier 1 failure on its minimal `participants.yaml` would read as the methodology contradicting its own D-023 bootstrap exemption.
