provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:91:> /provenance/
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:100:> Each session's provenance is a numbered directory. Files within are numbered for reading order. All provenance files use Markdown with YAML frontmatter:
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:102:> Provenance records are **immutable** once the session closes. Errors or retractions are recorded in subsequent sessions, not by editing past records.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:133:**Q2. Workspace-structure revision (W2).** Propose specific text (new section, revised section, or additions to existing sections) for `workspace-structure.md`. Your proposal should name where external artefacts live, how they are referenced, and what — if anything — distinguishes them from session-internal provenance artefacts. Options include (but are not limited to): new top-level `applications/` directory; canonicalize the session-provenance-embedded pattern Session 008 used; a hybrid with a reference-from-provenance pointer. Argue for your preferred option and against at least two alternatives. If your proposal creates or relocates files that already exist (the Session 008 artefact is one such), explicitly address what happens to those files: move, copy, symlink, leave in place with a forward pointer, or something else.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:153:Your response will be committed verbatim as provenance. It will be read by synthesis in conjunction with three other perspective responses. Your positions — including positions you hold reluctantly or conditionally — are recorded at their strongest. Do not soften them to anticipate synthesis. If you hold a position in tension with your role-specific stance, record the tension explicitly; the synthesis prefers honest tension to performed alignment.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:157:You are The Outsider. You are a non-Claude participant, chosen because your training lineage differs from the Claude model family's. Your stance is not adversarial by design; the value you bring is a distinct provenance of prior belief.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:213:> ### provenance/
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:218:> /provenance/
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:227:> Each session’s provenance directory contains the session’s reasoning records. Files within a session provenance directory that participate in reading order are numbered. Numbering applies to provenance records only.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:229:> Provenance records are **immutable** once the session closes. Errors or retractions are recorded in subsequent sessions, not by editing past records.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:241:> Each subdirectory corresponds to the session that produced the work-product. Files in `applications/` are referenced from the producing session’s provenance, but are not themselves part of the numbered provenance sequence.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:245:> When a closed past session has already placed an external work-product inside `provenance/`, that file remains in place as a historical witness. Regularization into `applications/` is done by copy-plus-reference, not by move or rename.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:249:The Session 008 artefact should not be moved. Moving it would alter the contents of a closed session’s provenance directory and undercut the immutability rule the methodology already relies on. I would instead create a copy in `applications/008-first-external-application/morning-unfurl.md` and record in Session 009 that this is the canonical discovery path for external readers, while the provenance copy remains the historical in-session witness.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:251:I reject canonizing the Session 008 embedded pattern. It keeps external outputs buried in reasoning logs and makes future readers hunt through provenance to find the thing the methodology actually produced. It also keeps directory semantics muddled: a folder defined as “historical reasoning records” would continue to contain user-facing outputs.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:253:I also reject a “pointer-only” hybrid where the real artefact stays in provenance and `applications/` merely points to it. That improves discovery a little, but it leaves the underlying classification problem untouched. The top-level location should contain the artefact itself.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:259:My preferred rule is: each session provenance directory must contain exactly one decisions file matching the naming pattern `NN-decisions.md`, where `NN` is the two-digit reading-order prefix. The tool should discover that file by pattern, fail if it finds none, and fail if it finds more than one. Checks 14 and 15 should then use the discovered path.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:263:I would not leave the tool as-is on the theory that moving external artefacts to `applications/` makes the numbering problem disappear. First, Session 008 already demonstrated that the current assumption was brittle enough to shape human behavior around the tool. Second, even if W2 is fixed, other future provenance insertions could still change numbering. A validator that only works when history happens to stay frozen in one exact pattern is underspecified.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:273:The second interaction is between Q1 and Q2 themselves. Once external artefacts live in `applications/`, domain-native validation records need an explicit object to point at. That is a good interaction, not a problem, but it should be made concrete in Session 009: the producing session’s provenance should reference the `applications/...` path, and the later validation record should reference the same artefact path when reporting results. I would treat that as bundled, not deferred, because otherwise the two revisions sit side by side without a specified linkage.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:275:The interaction with `multi-agent-deliberation.md` is mostly benign. The brief already records the important classification correction: W4 is D-023-triggering, W2 is not. That matters procedurally, but it does not by itself require a revision to the multi-agent spec unless that spec currently misstates the trigger list. On the facts given here, I would not bundle a spec edit there. I would record the correction in Session 009 provenance and leave the spec untouched unless a direct contradiction is later observed.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:279:So my split is: coordinated now for `validation-approach.md` and provenance-to-application cross-referencing; benign now for multi-agent trigger classification; future watchpoint for multi-artefact indexing.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:287:It satisfies **O** as well. The next named external action is straightforward: produce another external artefact, or revise the existing one if later feedback warrants it. The current ambiguity about `Validate` leaves unclear whether user/domain testing is part of the expected process, and the current ambiguity about artefact location leaves unclear where to put the result. Both narrow the action decision space once fixed.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:289:It satisfies **K** very strongly. A first-time outside reader would notice both problems quickly: `Validate` appears tool-centric and internal, while the workspace structure names provenance but not deliverables. These are not private housekeeping defects. They are visible mismatches between what the methodology says it is and what it has now done.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md:299:I expect some Claude perspectives to prefer keeping external artefacts inside session provenance for locality or minimal change. I think that is the wrong optimization: it preserves directory tidiness at the cost of a lasting category error between reasoning records and deliverables. A suspect assumption in the brief is that domain-native validation will usually arrive as user feedback; it should be framed more broadly as evidence from the relevant domain actor or setting. My main framing concern is that `tools/validate.sh` is close to becoming the de facto definition of `Validate`. The specification should discipline the tool, not inherit the tool’s accidental ontology.
