provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/archive/022-outsider/02-chunk.md:675:    33	Absorb what the session will reason from before changing anything. In every session this includes **workspace reading**: the full current state of the workspace — every file, every specification, every provenance record, and, where relevant, recent version-control history. Build a complete picture of the workspace's own state.
provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/archive/022-outsider/02-chunk.md:695:    25	Before doing any substantive work, read everything the workspace has preserved about prior decisions. If an idea was considered and rejected earlier, do not silently re-propose it. If you believe a rejected idea deserves reconsideration, cite the prior rejection and explain what has changed. Continuity of reasoning is the whole point of preserving provenance.
provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/archive/022-outsider/02-chunk.md:699:    29	The work should produce a concrete output: a structured record of what was proposed, what was decided, what was rejected with reasoning, and what remains uncertain. This record is the provenance. Commit it to the workspace in a way that preserves it permanently and makes it findable by future applications. Alongside the provenance, update or create whichever artefacts the work warrants. If the work produced a new specification, write the specification. If it produced an implementation, build it. If it surfaced problems, record them where subsequent work will find them. The structure of the workspace should evolve to serve the methodology, not the other way around.
provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/archive/022-outsider/02-chunk.md:701:    31	Before ending the session, verify the workspace is in a coherent state. Specifications describe the engine as it currently is. Validations pass against those specifications, or their failures are documented as open issues for subsequent work to address. Any human-facing summary of the workspace accurately reflects its current state. Every piece of work done in this session has committed its provenance.
provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/archive/022-outsider/02-chunk.md:713:    43	Preserve all provenance. Do not delete historical records, even when they feel embarrassing or outdated. A rejected idea from long ago may be the key to understanding a decision made today.
provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/archive/022-outsider/02-chunk.md:724:Selvedge is the methodology (abstract approach). The Selvedge engine is its current loadable implementation. This application is one specific run of that engine; it has its own inputs, its own artefacts, its own validation pathway, and its own provenance. The engine's development-provenance (the `SESSION-LOG.md`, `open-issues.md`, and `provenance/` of the source workspace where the engine was developed) is NOT part of this application's context unless explicitly imported by a decision in this workspace.
provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/archive/022-outsider/02-chunk.md:752:<<The engine version under which this application is running (e.g., `engine-v1`). Record this in every session's provenance so future readers know which engine behaviour applies. See `specifications/engine-manifest.md` §2 and §7.>>
provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/archive/022-outsider/02-chunk.md:764:- **Workspace reading** — the full current state of this application's workspace (this workspace, not the engine's source workspace). Every file, every prior session's provenance, every prior artefact in `applications/`.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:12:1. **`provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/`** — assessment, verbatim user Validate report, shared brief (anchor commit `3260f0b`), four raw perspective files (Reviser, Minimalist, Skeptic from parallel Claude Opus 4.7 subagents; Outsider from `codex exec` committed verbatim including banner, prompt echo, primary response, tokens line — 16,851 tokens — and end-of-stream duplicate), synthesised deliberation, decisions (D-053 through D-056, each declaring `**Triggers met:**` + `**Triggers rationale:**` inline per D-037/D-038), manifests for all four participants under `manifests/`, session-level `participants.yaml` with explicit participants list, and this close.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:16:3. **`specifications/workspace-structure.md` v2** — substantive revision per D-054. New top-level `applications/` directory defined with mutability semantics, organization-by-session, frontmatter requirements (`originating_session`, `regularized_in_session`, `provenance_witness_path`, `last-revised-session`), and copy-plus-reference regularization procedure for pre-existing external artefacts. §Additional directories updated to note `applications/` is no longer hypothetical. Two new Validation checks (6 and 7). v1 preserved as `workspace-structure-v1.md` with `status: superseded`.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:20:5. **`applications/008-morning-unfurl/morning-unfurl.md`** — new canonical copy of Session 008's external artefact, produced by copy-plus-reference per D-054. Frontmatter records `originating_session: 008`, `regularized_in_session: 009`, `provenance_witness_path: provenance/008-first-external-application/artefact-morning-unfurl.md`. The body is byte-identical to the Session 008 provenance copy's body. The provenance copy is untouched.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:59:   - **External artefacts have a canonical home** (D-054). `applications/008-morning-unfurl/morning-unfurl.md` is findable by external readers without provenance archaeology. Session 010+ sessions producing external artefacts adopt the canonical path from the start.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:61:   - **Copy-plus-reference mechanism preserves provenance immutability** (D-054). The Outsider-originated third-way resolves the mutability/immutability tension between external artefacts and provenance records without either side compromising.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:63:   - **Second consecutive session without a brief-priming finding.** Session 008 broke the three-session streak via disciplined brief-writing; Session 009 continues the practice. The Session 009 brief avoided Session 008's distinctive vocabulary ("representability bias", "preference instability", "hospitality package", "four-way convergence") and the "mutable"/"immutable" convergence arrived from three independent perspective framings rather than lexical echo from the brief.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:93:- **OI-004 sustained-practice closure criterion 2 is newly satisfied.** Session 009 is the third required-trigger deliberation with non-Claude participation (Sessions 005, 006, 009). Sessions 007 and 008 included non-Claude participation voluntarily without advancing the tally. OI-004 is now closable but not closed — criterion 4 (articulation of "substantively different training provenance") has not been deliberated. A future session may undertake closure; that deliberation is D-023-triggering in its own right (it asserts an OI-004 state change) and requires non-Claude participation.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:95:- **The 2-2 Q2 split resolved by Outsider's third-way is a substantive validation of heterogeneous participation.** The Claude-only perspectives produced a deadlock: Reviser wanted to move the artefact (violating immutability); Minimalist and Skeptic wanted to leave it in place (violating the applications/ premise). Neither Claude position accommodated both mutability of external artefacts and immutability of provenance. The Outsider's copy-plus-reference mechanism resolves the tension without requiring either side to surrender their substantive position. This is the third of the synthesis-acknowledged cross-model contributions and arguably the strongest in terms of outcome-shape — it did not merely influence wording but unblocked a decision.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:99:- **Brief discipline continues to improve.** Session 005 flagged the first brief-priming finding (training-distribution theatre). Session 006 flagged the second (consistency-not-truthfulness). Session 007 flagged the third (load-bearing, ritual-tracking). Session 008 broke the streak via disciplined brief-writing. Session 009's brief explicitly avoided Session 008's distinctive vocabulary and the convergent "mutable/immutable" framing arrived from three independent perspective framings rather than lexical echo. Two-session streak of brief-priming-absent; worth carrying forward as confirmed technique.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:103:- **Session 009 did not attempt OI-004 closure.** Criteria 1, 2, 3 are satisfied; criterion 4 (articulate "substantively different training provenance") is not. Closure requires deliberating what "substantively different training provenance" means operationally — e.g., what distinguishes a non-Anthropic model from a differently-initialised Anthropic-family model, or what criteria a human reviewer must meet. This is plausibly Session 010 or later work. The conservative stance is that closure requires its own deliberation, and the accumulation of qualifying data points does not in itself close an open issue.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:117:   - Whether the "mutable"/"immutable" convergence across three perspectives was genuinely independent or reflects shared Claude priors.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:123:   - **OI-004 closure deliberation.** Articulate criterion 4 ("substantively different training provenance" and enumerated acceptable participant kinds). This is D-023.4-triggering in its own right; requires non-Claude participation. Closure decision would be a substantial session focus and plausibly would not also accommodate other work.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/03-close.md:129:Session 009 is now closed. The workspace is in a coherent state: **4 active specifications** (2 newly revised to v2), **6 superseded preserved**, **9 provenance sessions**, **1 tool**, **1 `applications/` directory with 1 external artefact**, **12 open issues** (OI-004 closable-pending-criterion-4), **2 resolved** (OI-003, OI-010), **56 recorded decisions** (D-001 through D-056), and **5 heterogeneous-participant deliberations** with non-Claude participation (3 required-trigger; 2 voluntary).
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:50:- Reviser [01a, Q2]: "Provenance is immutable; external artefacts are mutable. Putting mutable artefacts inside immutable directories is a contradiction the workspace will pay for the first time an artefact is revised."
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:51:- Outsider [01d, Q2]: "Session 008's placement solved an immediate problem, but it did so by collapsing two different object types into one directory class… It keeps external outputs buried in reasoning logs and makes future readers hunt through provenance to find the thing the methodology actually produced."
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:56:- Skeptic [01c, Q2]: "This is n=1 architecture. We do not know whether future external artefacts will be one-off files, directories with sub-structure, or something else entirely… [it] severs the artefact from its producing session, which is exactly where its provenance lives."
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:58:**Three-of-four convergence on Session 008 artefact immutability.** Minimalist, Skeptic, and Outsider all refuse to move or modify the Session 008 artefact. [Minimalist, 01b, Q2]: "Session 008's provenance is closed; moving files out of a closed session violates the 'immutable once the session closes' property." [Skeptic, 01c, Q2]: "Nothing. It stays at `provenance/008-first-external-application/artefact-morning-unfurl.md`." [Outsider, 01d, Q2]: "The Session 008 artefact should not be moved. Moving it would alter the contents of a closed session's provenance directory and undercut the immutability rule the methodology already relies on. I would instead create a copy…" [01d, Q2].
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:60:**Reviser as lone mover.** [Reviser, 01a, Q2]: "Move `provenance/008-first-external-application/artefact-morning-unfurl.md` to `applications/008-morning-unfurl/artefact.md`." This position contradicts the immutability rule by its own author's reasoning — the Reviser's stance values precision and canonical location over a structural rule they did not weigh. The three-of-four convergence on immutability is the stronger synthesis signal.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:62:**Cross-model observation.** The Outsider's "copy-plus-reference" proposal is a structural innovation that no Claude perspective produced: the artefact is copied to `applications/`, while the provenance copy remains as a frozen historical witness. [01d, Q2]: "Regularization into `applications/` is done by copy-plus-reference, not by move or rename." This resolves the Reviser's immutability/mutability tension without requiring either side to surrender their substantive position. It is a synthesizer-adopted solution; credit is Outsider-original.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:64:**Shape of decision needed.** The 2-2 split on `applications/` yes/no is genuine. The synthesizer must make a judgment call. The strongest argument for `applications/` is structural: it cleanly separates reasoning records from deliverables, and the Outsider's copy-plus-reference honours provenance immutability. The strongest argument against is epistemic: pattern-claims-from-n=1 are brittle. Synthesizer's weighed recommendation is for `applications/` with copy-plus-reference, because (a) cross-model support exists (Outsider + Reviser), (b) the immutability-honouring copy-plus-reference mechanism defuses the strongest pragmatic objection, and (c) the Minimalist/Skeptic concern about premature pattern-commitment is real but reversible — applications/ can be deprecated if it does not earn its place, while embedding mutable artefacts in immutable provenance creates a structural contradiction that is not reversible.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:82:**Interaction-with-Q2 observation** [synth]: If Q2 adopts `applications/` (the synthesizer's recommended path), external artefacts leave the provenance directory. The provenance directory then reliably contains only the numbered reading-order files plus decisions, and the `02-decisions.md` hard-coded path is never at risk from external-artefact numbering pressure. The tool's silent-bypass hazard is *removed by the Q2 decision*, not by a tool fix. The Skeptic's "don't touch what isn't broken" argument is strengthened conditional on Q2's applications/ adoption.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:94:2. **Q1 × Q2 linkage**: Outsider [01d, Q4] argues for explicit artefact-path cross-referencing ("the producing session's provenance should reference the `applications/...` path, and the later validation record should reference the same artefact path when reporting results"). Reviser's proposal already embeds this via the `external-artefact.md` forward-pointer file [01a, Q2]. Minimalist [01b, Q4] says benign (slight duplication across two specs, not inconsistency).
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:96:   **Synthesizer resolution** [synth]: Adopt the Outsider's linkage principle but without adding a `external-artefact.md` forward-pointer file to Session 008's closed provenance directory (which would violate immutability). Instead: Session 009's decision record itself is the authoritative cross-reference from provenance to `applications/`. The `applications/008-morning-unfurl/morning-unfurl.md` copy's frontmatter records its originating session and the session that regularized it. The provenance copy's `artefact-morning-unfurl.md` is untouched. Future sessions that produce external artefacts will adopt the applications/ path as canonical from the start, and no forward-pointer-into-provenance file will be needed.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:108:- Q2 × `multi-agent-deliberation.md`: all four perspectives agree this is benign. The brief's D-023 classification correction is already recorded in Session 009's provenance; no spec edit to multi-agent-deliberation.md is warranted.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:137:**Brief-priming check.** Session 008 flagged "load-bearing / ritual-tracking / overdue / drift-to-ritual / domain-general" as Session 007 brief-seeded vocabulary. Session 009's brief deliberately avoided these. Checking Session 009's raw outputs: "load-bearing" appears in all four (but originates in G/O/K/S criterion 3 language, which is the brief's own; not a novel Session 009 seeding). "Mutable" / "immutable" were not seeded by the brief and arrived independently in three of four perspectives — **genuine structural convergence**, not lexical echo. "Domain-native validation" / "Domain validation" terminology arrived in three perspectives with different phrasings: "domain-native" (Reviser, Outsider), "domain" (Outsider), and unlabelled in Minimalist. Mild divergence on vocabulary suggests convergence on the concept rather than the phrase — a healthy signal.
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:152:2. **Adopt Q2 `applications/` directory with copy-plus-reference for Session 008 artefact.** Minimalist/Skeptic n=1 objection preserved. Copy to `applications/008-morning-unfurl/morning-unfurl.md`. Do not modify Session 008's closed provenance directory. Cross-reference anchored in Session 009's decision record (not as a new file in Session 008's provenance).
provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01-deliberation.md:162:6. **OI-004 sustained-practice tally advances 2 → 3 of 3.** Session 009 is a required-trigger deliberation (kernel revision → D-023.1; non-Claude present). Closure criterion 2 satisfied. Not automatically closable; criterion 4 (articulate "substantively different training provenance") remains unmet.
provenance/022-workspace-scaling-trajectory/archive/014-oi016-outsider/13-chunk.md:5:/Users/ericmccowan/.codex/sessions/2026/04/20/rollout-2026-04-20T11-10-25-019da870-4e49-7953-aaf9-572867d386fe.jsonl:6:{"timestamp":"2026-04-20T01:10:27.546Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"You are the **Outsider** perspective in a multi-agent design deliberation. Your response will be committed verbatim as the raw output of your perspective, including any CLI banner, session id, and reasoning-effort metadata your invocation emits.\n\n**INSTRUCTIONS:**\n- Respond with ONLY your answers to Q1–Q6 below.\n- Start your response with `## Q1. Shape` as the first line.\n- No preamble, no meta-commentary about the task, no closing summary.\n- Quote specific proposed wording verbatim where relevant.\n- Target 1200–2500 words total. Shorter if confident; longer only if required.\n\n---\n\n# SHARED BRIEF\n\n## 1. Methodology context\n\nYou are one of four perspectives in a multi-agent deliberation. The other three perspectives are reasoning independently from the same shared brief; you will not see their responses until after synthesis. The four perspectives are **Drafter**, **Mediator**, **Outsider**, and **Skeptic** (alphabetical). Three are parallel context-isolated instances of Claude Opus 4.7; the fourth (Outsider — you) is a non-Claude model from a different training lineage.\n\nThe methodology you are serving is a text-based design methodology that evolves by applying its own process to itself across repeated sessions. One artefact type it produces is an **external artefact** — a work-product intended for use outside the workspace, validated by whoever holds the problem the artefact addresses.\n\nSession 010 is the methodology's **second external application**. Session 008 produced a 4-minute lower-back morning movement sequence (\"Morning Unfurl\") that was validated positively by the user who requested it. Session 009 revised the methodology's kernel to name Domain validation as a first-class activity and created the `applications/` directory as the canonical home for external artefacts.\n\n## 2. Problem statement\n\nThe target is a **decision-making protocol for two people making a household decision of non-trivial cost and medium-term impact on the shape or function of their shared home**.\n\n### Context from the user (who will also be one of the two people trying the protocol)\n\n- **The two people.** The user and his wife. A couple sharing a household.\n- **Typical decision scope.** Roughly A$500 budget. Examples the user named: (a) what kind of storage shelving to install in the lounge — generic cube storage, or nicer bookshelves; (b) how to approach landscaping along the side of the house — pavers versus native plants.\n- **Stakes.** Medium-term satisfaction with how the house looks and functions. Not crisis-level. Not trivial.\n- **Frequency.** These conversations happen, but not weekly. A couple of such decisions are active right now, which means the artefact can be tried promptly.\n- **Who initiates.** In this couple, the user is the initiator of the process; his wife is the other party. The protocol should name these two positions but should be symmetric enough that either could initiate in principle.\n- **Validation.** The two people will try the protocol on a live decision and report back on: whether it worked; whether it read as casual and household-native rather than corporate or meeting-like; whether any step felt awkward, prescriptive, or unnecessary; whether the artefact could stand alone without explanation.\n- **User-declared constraints.**\n  - Must read as a **friendly household document**. Not corporate. Not \"meeting minutes\".\n  - **Format** can be a flow diagram, list of steps, cyclic sequence, or something else. Not prescribed.\n  - Users are **emotionally intelligent and psychologically secure** — protocol can be slightly more structured than average but must not require those qualities.\n  - Protocol **can assume trust**; no conflict-resolution machinery for hostile parties.\n\n### Non-goals\n\n- Not a general conflict-resolution framework.\n- Not a decision framework for groups larger than two.\n- Not a budgeting tool.\n- Not a decision-matrix calculator.\n- Not a relationship-therapy intervention.\n\n### Reference artefact\n\nSession 008's \"Morning Unfurl\" movement sequence is the aesthetic reference: practical, 1–2 printed pages, reader-respecting register, includes an explicit \"what this refuses\" section.\n\n## 3. Design questions\n\n- **Q1. Shape.** What overall shape should the protocol take? Options include: linear list of steps, cyclic flow (steps repeat per decision), branching decision tree, two-column dialogue layout, short set of rituals or \"moves\", one-page checklist, or something else. Justify against the specific context.\n- **Q2. Content.** What are the ~3–7 moments, steps, or moves the protocol should name? What does each one do? Which decision-making activities belong in the artefact (explicit), and which should be left to the people's judgment (not over-specified)?\n- **Q3. Register and tone.** How should it read? Specific language choices that signal \"friendly household\" rather than \"corporate process\". Consider: addressing the reader; first-person plural, second-person, or other; imperative or invitational; where humour or warmth belongs; what register-markers would be harmful.\n- **Q4. Handling emotional stakes.** Medium-term satisfaction; uneven caring between the two people on different decisions. How should the protocol acknowledge uneven stakes without escalating them, and without corporate-diversity-training gestures? What must it **not** do in this dimension?\n- **Q5. What the protocol refuses.** Choices by exclusion. Pick at least three and explain. Consider: voting thresholds, weighted scoring matrices, written justifications, time limits, third-party arbitration, explicit veto rights, mandatory cool-off periods, post-decision review.\n- **Q6. Meta / honest reaction.** Free-form. Disagreements with problem statement, missing critical context, hazardous framings, concerns about whether the methodology's domain-general claim extends to this domain at all.\n\n## 4. Role-specific stance — Outsider\n\nYou are the non-Claude participant in this deliberation. You are a model from a different training lineage than the other three perspectives, which are all instances of the Claude model family. Your structural role is to represent priors and framings the Claude-family perspectives may share without noticing — the \"training-distribution anchoring\" the methodology explicitly flags as a limitation of Claude-only deliberation.\n\nPriorities for your response:\n\n- Answer Q1–Q6 from whatever stance you find most productive. You are not required to adopt a specific professional role; you may lean closer to Drafter, closer to Mediator, closer to Skeptic, or independent of all three, as the question warrants.\n- In Q6 especially, name any phrasings or framings in the brief that you think would read as characteristically Claude — over-caveated, over-structured, or over-hospitable to the methodology's own abstractions. You are the one perspective in this deliberation that is not from the Claude family; use that.\n- Propose at least one concrete thing the other three perspectives are likely to miss — a structural feature, a tonal risk, a failure mode, a cultural assumption. Be specific; generic \"watch for X\" is not useful.\n- If you think the task is being overcomplicated relative to what two people making a household decision actually need, say so plainly. You do not need to protect the deliberation's assumption that a protocol is worth producing.\n\n## 5. Response format\n\n- Address Q1–Q6 in order, each with its own H2 heading (e.g., `## Q1. Shape`).\n- Target 1200–2500 words total.\n- State load-bearing positions plainly.\n- Quote language choices verbatim where you propose specific wording.\n- \"Pass with reason\" is acceptable provenance.\n\n## 6. Constraint on external imports\n\nReason primarily from this brief. If an idea arrives from elsewhere — pretraining, unrelated reading, personal experience, another domain — flag it explicitly as an external input (e.g., `external-input: from the facilitation literature, …`). Unflagged external inputs are a specification violation.\n\n---\n\nBegin your response now with `## Q1. Shape`.\n"}]}}
